10. Ne currente retro funis eat rota] ‘Lest the wheel turn back and the rope with it,’ is Orelli's interpretation, applying ‘retro' to both ‘currente’ and ‘eat.' The iuctaphor in that caseis taken from a rope wound round a cylinder, and when the cylinder is allowed to run back, the rope runs down and the weight or thing at- tached goes with it. The application of the proverb to a coquette who continues her pride till she loses her power is obvious. The passage has caused a good deal of dif- ficulty, and no two interpreters are entirely agreed as to the meaning of the words. Orelli's interpretation is the best that Ι have seen.
